The '''king rail''' ('''''Rallus elegans''''') is a waterbird, the largest [[North America]]n [[Rallidae|rail]].

==Description==
[[File:Blending in.jpg|thumb|At [[Huntley Meadows Park|Huntley Meadows]] in [[Virginia]]]]
Distinct features are a long [[beak|bill]] with a slight downward curve, with adults being brown on the back and rusty-brown on the face and breast with a dark brown cap. They also have a white throat and a light belly with barred flanks. Undertail coverts are white and are displayed by the male during courtship.<ref name=gnmb>{{cite web|url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/king-rail|website=Guide to North American Birds|publisher=National Audubon Society|title=King Rail|access-date=12 April 2023}}</ref>  Immature birds are covered in [[Down feather|down]],<ref name="Hauber2014"/><!-- Cites that they are covered in down--> with light brown on the head and darker brown on the back and wings.

This bird's [[bird song|call]] is a low repeated grunt transcribed as ''kek-kek-kek''.<ref name=BofCuba/>

